      "lotl": {
        "label": "What's Going On With the Jays",
        "body": "The defending AL champions are unraveling at precisely the wrong moment. Toronto sits at 16-19, third in the East and eight games back - not yet buried, but close enough to smell the dirt. <strong>Last night's 5-1 loss to Tampa Bay extended their skid to two straight</strong>, a pair of defeats that exposed what's been festering all May: a lineup that can't execute in tight spots and a pitching staff that's bleeding runs. The Rays, meanwhile, have won ten of their last eleven, a scorching pace that makes the Blue Jays' stumble look worse by the hour. Kazuma Okamoto has provided flashes of life - four home runs since May 1st, his sixth of the season - but one man's hot streak doesn't cure a team's malaise. Vladimir Guerrero Jr. and the rest of the order have gone quiet when it matters most. <strong>They head back to Tampa tonight for another crack at the Rays, a chance to stop the bleeding before this thing gets away from them entirely</strong>. Two games back against a team playing championship baseball. This is where seasons turn or end.",
        "updated": "Updated May 5, 2026"
      },
